      {
        "answer": "I can answer this from my knowledge without needing a web search.\n\nThe bebop scale is a variation of the major scale with an added chromatic note. In the key of A major, the bebop scale includes all the notes of the A major scale plus an added passing tone.\n\n**A Major Bebop Scale (ascending):**\nA - B - C# - D - E - F# - G# - G - A\n\nThe notes are:\n1. A (root)\n2. B (major 2nd)\n3. C# (major 3rd)\n4. D (perfect 4th)\n5. E (perfect 5th)\n6. F# (major 6th)\n7. G# (major 7th)\n8. G (flat 7th/passing tone)\n\nThe added chromatic note is the **G natural** (or flat 7), which falls between the major 7th (G#) and the octave (A). This creates the characteristic eight-note scale used in bebop jazz, providing smooth chromatic passages and a unique feel to improvisation.",
